"for the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

this piece is on sexual harassment and how consent is still an issue for women today. i personally have been sexually harassed, as early as junior high when boys thought it was appropriate to pull up my skirt and grab my chest... saying things such as â€œ show me your tits iâ€™ll give it backâ€... but thatâ€™s just boys being boys right? i think not. 
this piece is on the grey area of victims. â€œ well did you tell them no?â€ a simple no does not stop attackers from assaulting victims... we have to do better as a society to protect and hold those accountable for taking advantage of others! inspired by a photo i seen awhile ago. 
finished piece! had fun with the colors in this oil painting. probably the coolest artwork i have produced so far in my two years of painting! ğŸ˜Š

repost from @theconsciouskid â€œfor the first time in its 127-year history, the american psychological association has issued guidelines to help psychologists specifically address the issues of men and boys â€” and the document features a warning.
â€œtraditional masculinity ideology has been shown to limit malesâ€™ psychological development, constrain their behavior, result in gender role strain and gender role conflict and negatively influence mental health and physical health,â€ the report warns.

the new â€œguidelines for psychological practice with boys and menâ€ defines â€œmasculinity ideologyâ€ as â€œa particular constellation of standards that have held sway over large segments of the population, including: anti-femininity, violence, adventure, risk, achievement, and eschewal of the appearance of weakness.â€ the report links this ideology to homophobia, bullying, sexual harassment, and a series of stark statistics: men commit approximately 90 percent of all homicides in the u.s., they are far more likely than women to be arrested and charged with intimate partner violence in the u.s., and they are four times more likely than women to die of suicide worldwide.

the guidelines for psychologists outlined in the report include encouraging them to "recognize that masculinities are constructed based on social, cultural, and contextual norms"; "understand the impact of power, privilege, and sexism on the development of boys and men and on their relationships with others"; and "reduce the high rates of problems boys and men face and act out in their lives such as aggression, violence, substance abuse, and suicide." apa psychologist jared skillings said parents can play a part, too. he recommended they let their boys know, â€œitâ€™s ok to not be ok all the time.â€'
--tim fitzsimons, @nbcnews

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
i think it takes a lifetime of learning to understand yourself before you truly figure it out. 
we are all always changing & evolving. this is the nature of life.

i have lived many different lifetimes in this one alone. i'm sure you have too. 
time spent worrying about whether someone else understands you is time wasted. seek to understand yourself first. spend time with you. 
take yourself out on dates, do nice things for you, smile & love yourself.

remember that you're doing the best you can. and that's enough for now. â¤ï¸ #xtinaisms | #welltraveledwoman

text:
#deepthoughts by jess ruzz. what kinds of reflection and clarity do you find in your own stillness? âœ’ğŸ–¤ @thewordforthis 
my reflection â€“ not just how i see myself and others, but the actual act of examining â€“ is far more clear when iâ€™m emotionally, intellectually, and spiritually still. stillness happens when i turn off judgment and replace it with curiosity (to me, these are an important pair of opposites), and often, acceptance. 
sometimes itâ€™s because i need to heal, to treat myself with more kindness or to protect myself from further damage, whether as a survivor or simply as a human being capable of being hurt. sometimes itâ€™s because i need to find and implement ways to be better and do better â€“ as an advocate, as a professional, as a spouse and parent and friend, in anti-racism self-education and practice (which arose specifically out of the work iâ€™m doing here, but which is woven into all of the roles i occupy in life), as a feminist... in any place where iâ€™m a human being capable of getting it wrong or causing pain. in either case, seeing myself and others clearly is an ongoing process, and a living, breathing goal.

text: iâ€™ve worked so hard on myself these past two years and i continue to work on myself. it never ceases to amaze me that iâ€™ve gone from spending my days in bed clutching a bottle of pills debating on just taking a few or taking the whole bottle to finding a job that i love, my own apartment, reconnecting with old friends, connecting with new friends and most importantly learning that a traumatic experience does not define who i am. i can only hope that sharing my experiences will help someone else see that they too can overcome anything. my goal is to be a positive presence and to allow people to be comfortable with who they are. #peaceandlove #suicideawareness #overcomingtrauma #metoo #learningtoloveyourself #positivevibes #lovetoall #bethegoodintheworld

after watching the @redtabletalk on r. kelly yesterday, i was led to watch the lifetime series @survivingrkelly . the layers and layers of these combined stories are soooo disheartening!! not only because they are all so similar but, also because of the bubble that has been created around this man to create the ecosystem where this can continue to occur. over 20 years! 
_____
this has escalated under the radar of every fan, reporter, record label, industry mate.... there are so many more people that know whatâ€™s been going on that have been more concerned about their paychecks than these women.
_____
this isnâ€™t the story of â€œfast little girlsâ€ this is a story of a manipulative predator that needs to be shut down along with evry single person over the years that has assisted in creating this sex  trafficking rape culture around him. this is disgusting and has been covered up for far too long.
_____
every lawyer, manager, assistant, security guard, and even the police officers that have been on his payroll should go to jail as far as iâ€™m concerned! there is too much of a track record. too much google accessible evidence and too many families completely destroyed!!! ğŸ˜¡
_____
the hashtags or even this post isnâ€™t enough and iâ€™m not too sure how to get involved outside of not playing his music but conversations will definitely be had with the girls and men in my family about how these things occur and go without being dealt with in our societies and homes.... so many small things that lead up into this ecosystem of abuse. ____

text:
men sometimes slide into my dms to tell me how i should be careful with kali worship. that it will destroy my nervous system or body, that i may be "doing it wrong". others tell me to my face that i don't understand her and that she's not "angry." but kali is everything and most certainly does express anger. she is an advocate and instigator of change. and she is the cheerleader /protector  of the marginalized. so yes anger arises to challenge complacency, bigotry, oppression. if you read that with fear its ok. the fear subsides when you witness the transformation. the alchemy of change is fierce at times, other time smooth, fluid. - maybe something about what im doing and my relationship to her challenges the post-ancient traditional concepts of kali devotion. but thats all part of the divine play. we're all going to the same place but theres no one way to get there. jai ma !
.
.

there are hindu and tantric practices that have rules and techniques and if you are not of those cultures and lineages then i really don't advise capitalizing and speaking on them.but as a person of the south asian diaspora by way of indentureship our relationship to culture/ religion/ goddess is delicate + ancient. we are the carriers of pre-colonialist seeds of magic and prayer. we deserve to sprout and grow as we wish. our guides come in with what we need to know (living and from the beyond) .
.

text:
for years, americans have shrugged their shoulders over nsa surveillance and government access to digital data and said, â€œi donâ€™t care; i have nothing to hide.â€ now they are starting to see that maybe they do have something to hide. they are starting to understand that their own preferences and those of their friends and family can be hoovered up and stored in perpetuity and fed through algorithms to produce manipulative messaging intended to move beliefs and influence actions.

although regulators and state attorneys general are launching investigations, the real hammer will be the market. whether it is facebook, twitter, or some other social media platform, when users start to realize that the data they are sharing may be used against them or cause them to lose control over their beliefs or be manipulated, they will begin to shut off. if the company canâ€™t be trusted with personal data, users simply will not use that platform and advertisers will go elsewhere.

roger mcnamee, mark zuckerbergâ€™s long-time mentor, saw the risk early on and tried to get facebook executives to manage it, but his warnings fell on deaf ears.  in an interview with christiane amanpour, mcnamee said that in october 2016, he personally warned zuckerberg and sheryl sandberg of the magnitude of the risk, but failed to get their attention. according to mcnamee, facebookâ€™s leaders kept arguing that facebook is a platform company, not a media company and â€œweâ€™re not responsible for what third parties do.â€ mcnamee warned them then, - you have 1.7 billion members and if they decide you are responsible, it wonâ€™t matter what the law says.

jody westby

text:
grateful and blessed to be given the opportunity to help individuals and the community of @msu @eastlansing heal through the power of art  and social practice. 
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text: social media has severely vexed my spirit the past few days. i'm trying to hold on for ministry purposes. it is disturbing how nasty, cruel, dismissive, and willfully ignorant people on facebook and instagram are toward sexual abuse survivors. this heart letter to my fellow survivors, who were stirred up in some way after #survivingrkelly, is the result of my grieved spirit. some of you, i clearly never knew you at all. it's unsettling my soul. p.s. zero tolerance for anyone who comes on trying to deflect from this predator, because this post is not about him in the least bit. itâ€™s about who some people are forgetting in their war of words, scramble to shut people up, and proud exclamations they will continue supporting abusers- the survivors.

text:
i have referenced as far as why i don't believe in the bible word for word. allow this to be one post that proves one of the reasons. i strongly disagree with the way the bible spoke about #women. i get it, the way they talked back in the day was much different but to excuse all of it is ludicrous. like for example, in the book of #corinthians, paul is speaking about how women should be covered by a veil (because man is the image and glory of god but woman is glory of the man) and how man isn't for woman but woman is for man.
1. this concept goes against the whole #gay argument. how is it the women is for men but men ain't for women? juvenile but so is this notion that women are only here for men. (you'll notice a theme here).
2. this goes against the number one reason we're here, to be fruitful and multiply. how are suppose to multiply if women are just here for men? we all have children thanks in large part to women taking care of themselves and respecting themselves. how can they if they worried bout is #men?
3. what good is god if all he truly cared for was men? why even dignify this crack head logic that women need to be covered and kept at home because they not in the image of god? whoever has seen god went blind (except very few which we don't have any direct quotes from. only heresay.) why would god create something so meaningless? and why think it's all about man when we see what happens when it is? (just look at history for 28283838383838383 examples)
4. the book was largely used as tool to spring other motives. one was the empowerment of man. to think that every word in the bible has whole intent would be ignorant. considering this was written years after death, roman catholics have manipulated so much of it, a lot of is still at the #vatican so the stories could be strategically put for a bigger message, and man has long yearned to be god and you can see why the bible is a message, not a religion.

text: day 3-4 today for my post from last night didnâ€™t go through ğŸ™ˆğŸ’ day 3 post of my personal body positivity challenge. 30 day of me posting personal things that people have said to me about my weight (which is due to illness) my story at a glance. i used to be 147 pounds until a crohns flair up and hospitalization and other illnesses drove me down to 76 pounds in 2015. then got pregnant with my daughter less than 6 months later and my body had not recovered and somethings are still getting worked out by doctors and we donâ€™t have all the answers yet. i didnâ€™t know skinny shaming was a thing. working in the service industry as a bartender and being an artist (a singer, actress and a visionary) during these few years has given me a unique outlook on my look. i got torn down to nothing with demeaning comments emotionally and physically i was in pain and mentally exhausted. then one day someone said something to me about my weight for the first time so innocently and i laughed and laughed and laughed and i said i can either have a field day with this or be miserable so letâ€™s have a field day!! and it was months before i truly started executing perfect come backs and everything really started to actually bounce off without effecting me. so this is 29 days of my favoriteshitty things iâ€™ve heard about my weight. then the best part is the 30th day about accepting your own kind of beauty and love. a video will be posted â¤ï¸ğŸ¤— thanks for joining me on my journey â¤ï¸ğŸ’ªğŸ¤— who this fuck says this?!?! hahahahaha #selflove #beauty #kindness #loveyourself #metoo #timesup #survivor #hopeful #invisibleillness #trustyourheart #glutenfree #believe #youdeservemore #bodypositive #bodypositivity #laughing #learning #growth #selflove #womenforwomen #womensupportingwomen

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text: the way to stop abusing yourself is to start really loving yourself. really truly deeply, deep down behind closed doors in your thoughts, heart, and mind, in your decisions, actions, and behavior. you have to learn to love yourself and find all the places your beating yourself up and stop. self love when you havenâ€™t been taught what that means sounds like an abstract word that you donâ€™t have meaning for. i had no clue what it meant, because i wasnâ€™t shown much. i was abandoned  abused, treated like trash, ignored, not taken seriously thrown away, so thatâ€™s how i treated myself. i was shown over and over again  that i had no value or worth at all. i began learning  self love out of a book,  but it has taken years to learn how to apply it. what does self love look like? it can mean different things for all of us because we all are nurtured in different ways but good self care is a start. you need to take good care of yourself on all levels; mind, body, emotions, soul. it means to treat yourself like you are a precious child that is deserving of softness and tenderness and kindness. love should never have to be earned you deserve it simply for existing. and if you exist itâ€™s because god wants you here, i promise you. i 100% know that we are spiritual beings having a human experience iâ€™ve seen and experienced first hand way too much to doubt it. my beliefs didnâ€™t come from a book. the work i do helps people penetrate past the veil so that they too can begin to see there is so much more to this life.  take good care of your body; get good rest, exercise, eat your vegetables and high quality food, drink lots of water, take vitamins, get your hair done, your nails done, but yourself clothes you like. take good care of your teeth, get checkups when you need them. feel your emotions; donâ€™t stuff them; know your worth. find people that care about your feelings and stay away from toxic poisonous people. know that you have the right to exist and have feelings and emotions and opinions that are worthy of respect. accept yourself deep down truly and deeply flaws and all. get healings, nurture your inner child( contâ€™d)

text:
jumah mubarak! as you may know, at the end of my podcast i ask my guests the same 3 questions. one of them is, who would you like to put our heads, hands, and hearts in dua for (our minds, souls, and acts). here's zenaâ€™s response from the #muslimmetoo podcast on the rogue muslim. .
.
.
tw: sexual violence, gender-based violence, poverty, abuse, spiritual, economic, physical, psychological, and sexual abuse, systems of violence. 
hi everyone :) this week i have zena on from sakeenah homes - a muslim women's shelter in canada.

we discuss: - why we need muslim women's shelters - ways to make shelter's more inclusive for muslim women - how to continue and maintain the connection folks have to their communities - which people feel they may lose because of how taboo these topics are - how to identify safe people to disclose to/ how to indicate you are a safe person - patriarchal interpretations of the quran - tips on recognizing cultures of abuse - how to put islam into the safety, healing, and change process

it is essentially a continuum of the #muslimmetoo movement, but please do not feel you need to listen to it, if you are not in a space to do so, or feel that you have to share you story to people. .

hi everyone :) this week i have zena on from sakeenah homes - a muslim women's shelter in canada.

we discuss: - why we need muslim women's shelters - ways to make shelter's more inclusive for muslim women - how to continue and maintain the connection folks have to their communities - which people feel they may lose because of how taboo these topics are - how to identify safe people to disclose to/ how to indicate you are a safe person - patriarchal interpretations of the quran - tips on recognizing cultures of abuse - how to put islam into the safety, healing, and change process

it is essentially a continuum of the #muslimmetoo movement, but please do not feel you need to listen to it, if you are not in a space to do so, or feel that you have to share you story to people. .

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
21) the upside - (@theupsidefilm) - 3 out of 5 freddie b's

starring: kevin hart (@kevinhart4real), bryan cranston (@bryancranston), nicole kidman (@nicolekidman)

movie leaves some loose ends important to the movie unanswered. the film is like a nice garment with loose frayed fibers all over it. various pieces of the plot were interjected and it seems like they were more so as a means to an end, to accomplish something further down the line in the movie.

the plot is done well of showing the relationship between kevin hart and bryan cranston and making you care about it. but the movie just barely clears the bar of keeping your interest. the events that happen along the way aren't fleshed out well whatsoever and would've been more just had we had less events that were interwoven more.

the plot has its layers of kevin hart life and bryan cranston's life. it's not layered as it could be. the plot does just enough to keep it from being completely linear. a few of the moments between kevin and bryan feel a little contrived and predictable but it isn't too bad.

beginning of the movie starts off average with a oft used method by using a high energy scene from later in the movie. here, it is executed a little better than average, albeit, it hurts the pacing of the movie later on in the film.

the ending is very quickly wrapped up almost like they were floating by and then realized "oh! it's been almost 2 hours!" acting by everyone is well done with no drop offs in actor performance by anyone.

kevin hart role in a more serious role is a good turn. he does add his signature funny quirks and it's well done and provides a nice touch.

overall, this is a movie that just barely clears the bar of just about everything it attempts to do. i can see how this was supposed to be that movie in the awards race but it ultimately just doesn't have enough "meat on the bone." if you see it in theaters, you won't be disappointed but this is one you could (and should) wait to see it at home.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytic until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
as a glistening foetus, 
uterus walls sang him lullaby of
a certain him abducting and 
another him rescuing a her
and of a her's dignity
measured in six yards. 
in second standard, 
thomas brought for him light. 
but only at matriculation, 
he learnt of currie, the 
cure to thomas's failure. 
seventh grade recited 
about young jalaluddin to him
and lessons on bakarwals 
helped him with geopolitics
of kathua. 
as adolescence assumed, 
homogeneity of flesh
ripe with facts and fiction
of puckish prejudice, 
pronged into a two tined fork
cleansing it was sister's task
and clanging nailheads, his. 
stifling below the rubble 
of this oblivious obviousness
became everyday, 
a slight stumble here, 
lifting extra kilos 
with pretentious ease
and a little gulp there
of tears and fears. 
until he was 
scrambled and screwed
like eggs and in orifices
pinched and ravished
at his sense and skeleton. 
failing the experiment
of mutating men for robots and
falling off while escalating stairs
of executing expectations. 
stuffed till brim
with generalisation 
and genderization, 
he couldn't take 
the leap of faith
so, he took to the loop. 
suicide shouted 
what masculinity feared, 
rape. .- @themysticforce

text:
today makes the 2nd anniversary of my very personal liberation as a rape survivor. it was 2 years ago that i chose to face the man who raped me in court. that was before #metoo happened. 
i faced what didn't seem possible to look straight into the eye cuz of the terror i felt still in my system then - after 21 years. 
to my surprise what i saw and didn't want to see was #humanity. in it's full spectrum. from the worst to the best in that court room. what i experienced was benevolence, justice, dignity and honor in the truth being revealed. 
i have shared my story publicly and i will do it again. because i know this isn't my story alone. i couldn't have faced this man on my own. i walked in connected to many people with similar stories. i felt that support energetically in my back and the wave of liberation in me blast right into the collective. maybe i was lucky to receive justice but i also did my work. i never had imagined i had the substance to stand in that intensity again and walk away lighter with less karma, more dignity, a new sense of safety in my cells (that hasn't left me) and the power of my presence reclaimed. 
since then much of sexual abuse in the world has been publicly revealed to find healing, clearing, justice and most of all liberation. liberation happens in revealing and owning all our parts in this ancient power game. we know blame just gaslights this game. 
liberation is a choice. reclaiming that we have a choice we deeply need to trust that we matter. and our live counts. 
i believe, we came here for a reason. whatever happened on our life path has the potential to empower us to change the world for better or worse. we can make a conscious choice to honor our path and bust out of our limitations to liberate our truth, our life force, our creative expression as a gift to ourselves & this world (essentially same thing) to create the changes we long to experience and find our way back to deeply felt connection. so we can take the right action needed to honor, respect, protect and innovate ourselves, this planet, humanity and creation itself. 
this is who i call change agents & daring leaders. claim it. be it. you matter!
#theartofrevealing

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
ever since i watched #survivingrkelly, i have reflected on my own experiences with sexual harassment in the workplace and academia. it is frustrating to know there is an infrastructure that protects (mainly) men  and demonizes the victims. it's not just r&b, hip hop, and rock & roll.
â€¢
in 2017, a survey conducted by the veterinary information network (a large web based vet professional community) found that over 40% of responders had experienced and witnessed sexual harassment in the workplace. over 2,300 individuals participated.
â€¢
veterinary medicine is considered a female dominated field yet the stats are the same as the national average if not higher. something needs to be done. it is not acceptable. i wish i had been mentored on how to handle these kinds of situations but unfortunately i had to learn on the fly. now i  know better. when i see something, i say something...and i keep a record of it. do your best to hold your employer accountable. you shouldn't need to "tough it out."

today makes the 2nd anniversary of my very personal liberation as a rape survivor. it was 2 years ago that i chose to face the man who raped me in court. that was before #metoo happened. 
i faced what didn't seem possible to look straight into the eye cuz of the terror i felt still in my system then - after 21 years. 
to my surprise what i saw and didn't want to see was #humanity. in it's full spectrum. from the worst to the best in that court room. what i experienced was benevolence, justice, dignity and honor in the truth being revealed. 
i have shared my story publicly and i will do it again. because i know this isn't my story alone. i couldn't have faced this man on my own. i walked in connected to many people with similar stories. i felt that support energetically in my back and the wave of liberation in me blast right into the collective. maybe i was lucky to receive justice but i also did my work. i never had imagined i had the substance to stand in that intensity again and walk away lighter with less karma, more dignity, a new sense of safety in my cells (that hasn't left me) and the power of my presence reclaimed. 
since then much of sexual abuse in the world has been publicly revealed to find healing, clearing, justice and most of all liberation. liberation happens in revealing and owning all our parts in this ancient power game. we know blame just gaslights this game. 
liberation is a choice. reclaiming that we have a choice we deeply need to trust that we matter. and our live counts. 
i believe, we came here for a reason. whatever happened on our life path has the potential to empower us to change the world for better or worse. we can make a conscious choice to honor our path and bust out of our limitations to liberate our truth, our life force, our creative expression as a gift to ourselves & this world (essentially same thing) to create the changes we long to experience and find our way back to deeply felt connection. so we can take the right action needed to honor, respect, protect and innovate ourselves, this planet, humanity and creation itself. 
this is who i call change agents & daring leaders. claim it. be it. you matter!
#theartofrevealing

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

police responded to a call claiming r. kelly was holding two women hostage. 
the demise of r. kelly is only beginning. following lifetimeâ€™s surviving r. kelly docuseries, the singer was put under a spotlight after allegations of sexual abuse resurfaced. heâ€™s currently under investigation in fulton county, ga while chicago police are looking for more information before they begin prosecution. while the singerâ€™s maintained a relatively low-profile since the docuseries aired, he recently had a run-in with police who were called to check in on two women who were allegedly being held captive by kellz.

according to tmz, police responded to an anonymous call which claimed r. kelly was holding two women hostage. the cook county state attorneyâ€™s office received a tip earlier today that the singer was at his trump tower residence with two women and he was holding them captive. police rushed to the property after receiving the call and made contact with kellz and the two women. 
five officers made their way to the property, ordering kellz into a separate room while they questioned the women. chicago pd said both women were there by choice and nothing strange was going on. police left the scene afterward without making any arrests.

the two women were joycelyn savage and azriel clary. the formerâ€™s parents have been in an on-going battle with kellyâ€™s team to try and make contact with their daughter. the parents of both women have already stated they believe kellz brainwashed their daughters. 
this is the second time this week police pulled up on r. kelly. police went to a chicago club earlier this week after they got a tip that said kellz was at the club and a warrant was issued for his arrest. police ultimately determined there wasnâ€™t any actual warrant out for the singerâ€™s arrest and eventually, let him go. get the full details at www.itskenbarbie.com #rkelly #robertkelly #survivingrkelly #muterkelly #trappedinthecloset #metoo #lifetime #lifetimetv #trumptower #entertainment #entertainmentnews #entertainmentblog #gossip

text:
[2.3] #fbf | back in marilynâ€™s era, receiving an award meant one thing above all others: being acknowledged for oneâ€™s talent and the years of dedication to perfect the art of acting. while the public praises the excellence of the final outcome (the on-screen performance), awards tend to acknowledge the apparently invisible efforts behind it, which usually went unnoticed. 
_______________

throughout her career, marilyn was nominated for four @goldenglobes and won three. 
in 1957 she was nominated for best actress in a leading role for bus stop, produced by her own marilyn monroe productions and starring one of her most dramatic and beloved performances.

in 1960 she won best actress for the cult comedy someone like it hot directed by billy wilder, opposite jack lemmon and tony curtis, and attended the ceremony with the glamorous nonchalance confidence of a white fur stole, as to symbolize the piece of mind and maturity she had reached as both an actress and a woman.

text:
mighty and strong like 
the mountain she stands,
courageous and fearless,
her powers,
she understands.
deep and vast like 
the ocean she's mysterious,
calm or chaotic, so unpredictable
yet every ounce of her is glorious.
mild like the zephyr and
ferocious like the gale, she blows,
in her heart, no grudge, no malice
she ever holds.
forgiving and serene like the earth 
she soothes every soul she meets,
every being in the universe,
she completes.
she's the goddess, 
she's the zenith
she's in everyone of us;
she's the satan
she's the nadir,
she's the universe rejoicing, thus.
.
.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
today is the day

that most people

realise 
there is more to life than diets

hurayyyyyyyy!

the average diet lasts 12 days.

and the average women does a minimum of 4 different diets per year.

so if my maths are as good as they use to be that's 48 days of dieting per year.

that's over a month and a half per year.

just a thought this saturday afternoon.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
the thing about trauma is that it isnâ€™t something that goes away, itâ€™s something that you learn to cope with. the reason iâ€™ve shared my story twice in the past is because sometimes i canâ€™t sleep. i canâ€™t think. my trauma and all the events leading up to it play like a movie over and over again in my mind that i actually feel myself starting to fall apart. recently, iâ€™ve been struggling. i havenâ€™t been able to shake the uncontrollable desire to confront my rapist. and every time i think about what i want to say, the message changes. sometimes itâ€™s angry, sometimes iâ€™m vindictive, sometimes i want to walk right up to him and scream at him until my lungs give out and i dissolve into dust. sometimes i want to cry. sometimes i want to curse him and wish the worst. sometimes i want to scream at my 15-18 year old self, sometimes i want to beg myself why, why was i with him?sometimes i want to scream at my 25 year old self for still remembering every sordid detail from when i met him in 2007 till when he realized there was nothing left of me to use and left in 2012. but this is healing. this is trauma. itâ€™s more than a â€œonce upon a nightmareâ€ story that i share twice a year, itâ€™s a daily struggle. healing is not a linear journey that has a start and finish line. healing is a roller coaster that never ends, its running in intervals. itâ€™s a process that lasts a lifetime.
all that being said: ive been struggling for the past couple of weeks on what i could possibly say to him if i actually did confront him. what am i looking for? what am i hoping to gain from this? an apology from him would be dishonest, and i wouldnâ€™t believe it. id like to believe that he could one day acknowledge what he did, but i donâ€™t know if thatâ€™s possible. 
in the end i came up with this letter and have decided to post it to my public instagram. this letter, this post, isnâ€™t just for him. itâ€™s for all the people i know struggling with trauma. i want to be transparent because damn it, this kind of struggle isnâ€™t talked about enough. know that itâ€™s ok to not be â€œoverâ€ it, know that itâ€™s ok to feel like this. know that you are not alone. 
#survivor #metoo #timesup #empowereachother

text:
because right now. the day that i have a son is the day i fear the evils of this world.

my american dream

black boys running free
laughing loudly
walking proudly
owning who they are
black boys in shopping malls
looking around
perusing the grounds
without causing alarm
black boys ridinâ€™ in cars
turn signal right
both tail lights
no fear in their hearts
black boys living life
treated fairly
murdered rarely
and justice does its part
black boys forever protected
family hugs â€˜em
country loves â€˜em
no daily battle scars

alexasym

text:
***trigger warning*** pt. 1: ptsd / sexual assault .
.
.
.
.
a common theme of my online presence has been little anecdotes of life after trauma. iâ€™ve been asked a lot lately about why iâ€™ve become quite quiet on this for the last 12-18 months in particular and itâ€™s because, well, things are simply quite good. i dare say the journey never ends but it is one kick starts new journeys that better take the forefront of our minds. whilst it is a privilege to have a voice in this realm, it is also necessary sometimes to be still and silent with your past because it is exactly that, the past. for a long time, it was healthy for me to talk about it, it helped me process it and learn from it and now, in turn, be still with it. whilst i am not adverse to discussing my narrative or the way it has shaped me and my life thereafter, i have little left to process and for me, thatâ€™s what it was all about - it was process where in order for it to make sense to me, i needed to learn how to make it make sense to somebody else. i used language as a way to deconstruct my dissonance and social media made me accountable in that process. whilst i am eternally touched and grateful to those who have reached out over the years, my motive was first and foremost a selfish one. sharing the nuances of how trauma shaped my life no longer serves me a greater purpose, in fact, i think to fixate on it too much now would be to refuge in misfortune. now, there is so much goodness that shapes my life, more prominently and prevalently, and it is something i am quite happily enjoying more privately. that said, i remain an open book and am all ears to those who want to reach out so, please donâ€™t be afraid to connect still. and i still welcome questions of any variety because for i whole heartedly believe that for as long as people are asking questions, they are not making assumptions. no matter what the capacity, we are in this together. cheers the years of solidarity. #ptsd #metoo #ptsdawareness

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
hope....
many people experience feeling somewhat broken when it comes to sex and sexuality. 
i definitely felt that way at times - as if there was something wrong with me, and yes, unfixable, broken.
.
but we we are not broken!
we might be hurt or have not had the right education, including sex ed, we might not have had the right environment to thrive. .
we might have been shamed for our sexuality or our boundaries might have been violated at some point. we might have shut down and protected ourselves. we might have numbed out.
.
we might need kindness, gentleness and care in order to heal, to unfold and thrive.
but we are not broken! .
for me amongst coaching, learning and community, it were creative tools that helped me hugely along the way: free writing, collage and painting helped me explore my sexuality and all its facets and supported me in my healing.
movement and many embodiment tools helped me to connect deeply with my body and express myself. .
not broken, but healing and rising!
.
if you want to explore where you are at with your sexuality and see how somatic sex education and sexological bodywork can support you, please get in touch for a free chat. contact in link in bio.
.
ğŸ’œ
#notbroken #eroticlife #sexualauthenticity #reclaimyoursexuality #backtosex #getbacktosex #metoo #rising #sexualhealing

i enjoy my workplace. i like the people, i like the work and i have made some amazing friends both patrons and the staff. we are a local cafe, the food is great and same with the coffee. however, being touched by strangers as a worker is not okay. twice this has happened to me in the last year. two seperate occasion patrons, for whatever reason have broken my personal boundaries and have touched me inappropriately. in the moment i have had no idea what to do. i freeze up. and both times, i have walked away thinking to myself â€œnext time, i am going say something and stand up for myselfâ€. and actually saying something is really hard and iâ€™m not sure how to approach it or what to even say. 
but for all of you out there, please donâ€™t touch the staff who are serving you. they are doing their job and respecting you and you should respect them. #metoo #respect

text: feeling a little bit like â€˜alice in wonderlandâ€™ today, standing in front of geneva-based artist mai thu perretâ€™s giant tea pot. for the artwork called â€˜little planetary harmonyâ€™ perret unceremoniously inverts scale. the silver teapot stands in the exhibition space of @mamco_geneve like a ufo of sorts, an object challenging spatial definition and interpretation. the sense of disorientation continues inside the interior of the pot, where a small series of hung artworks suggests a museum within a museum and sounds, when visitors speak to each other, take on an eerie quality. perretâ€˜s art, that you can still discover in a special retrospective until the 3rd of february, is more than often not obvious and declined in a multitude of different media,  from ceramic to wicker art, tapestry, sculpture or video/audio installations.

text:
trigger warning: rape and rape culture
â€¢
i watched the @redtabletalk special on 'surviving r kelly: the aftermath'. like all the times before as a survivor i am feeling this sense of heaviness, this deep sadness. my mind goes: "not again, not again with the scrutiny of victims, victim blaiming. again they don't believe us. again we are being attacked." when i was raped i knew it wasn't me, but i kept my mouth shut, didn't even called it rape for the first 10-15 years.
â€¢
i made this picture for project unbreakable in 2013, and it got posted there. i am putting it out again. not because all survivors should speak, because we all should get the respect to deal and heal from it in our own way.
â€¢
i am feeling so tired from always having to brace myself, and never being fully seen and met in the toll it takes on you to have to deal with denial, scrutiny and attacks, while it wasn't on you in the first place. can you just be with me while i cry for the (already 32) years of knowing you gonna get blaimed, knowing you will be roasted again because it is appearently too hard to face up to the fact that it does happen right under your nose?  can you just sit, shut up and listen, listen for all survivors? all that is required is to listen and then do better. we're not looking for approval, we already know it happened because we were there.
â€¢
#rapeculture #metoo #unbreakable #projectunbreakable #survivingrape #survivingsexualviolence #survivingsexualharasment #stopvictimblaiming #survivor

text:
when i talk about @youngboxingwoman i face either the assumption that we are some sort of social work based initiative trying to 'save'  the underprivileged. or that we are teaching self defense to save women from the attackers in the street. both of which are the opposite to our aims. 
i am not empowering women, they have already got all they need, im just working to balance out the overwhelming pressure society places on them to be less than they are, and to put up with more then they should. 
only 2% of assaults are by strangers, 98% are by close friends or family members. one woman a week is killed by her domestic partner. the self defense we need is not a cool wrist flick, but knowing we are worth enough to demand respect. 
women at every level and socioeconomic level face these same issues. private school or juvie. failing to acknowledge that is patronizing wishing.
#whatareyouangryabout

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
â€¢ one in four girls and one in six boys will be sexually abused before they turn 18 years old. â€¢ 30% of women were between the ages of 11 and 17 at the time of their first completed rape. â€¢ 12.3% of women were age 10 or younger at the time of their first completed rape victimization. â€¢ 27.8% of men were age 10 or younger at the time of their first completed rape victimization. â€¢ 96% of people who sexually abuse children are male. â€¢ 76.8% of people who sexually abuse children are adults. â€¢ 34% of people who sexually abuse a child are family members of the child. â€¢ in the u.s., one in three women and one in six men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime. â€¢ 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female, and nine percent are male. 
statistics curtesy of nsvrc.org (national sexual violence respirce center)

as a woman who was sexually abused as a child, this picture speaks volumes - right down to the shiny wedding band. i know the way you as an innocent child, while maybe at first you didn't realize anything was wrong, as you got older you started to feel uncomfortable but you couldn't quite understand what was happening yet. maybe he was a family friend who told you it was a fun "game" just for the two of you. maybe he was a dad or stepdad who said "shhh, don't tell mommy our little secret!" maybe he tried to convince you that it was "natural" to be naked. he made your desire to be clothed and untouched seem wrong. he made you question your conscience and your sanity. i understand your confusion, i understand your fear, i understand your hurt, i understand your anger, i understand your humiliation. realizing what was done to you is a major step in overcoming. the next steps: know it was not your fault. know that you are still beautiful, pure, and worhty. know that you don't have to carry around your guilt or your embarrassment or your shame. the victim is never to blame. be brave & find your voice - i know it's painful to talk about what happened. for me, it was almost impossible to put the images and memories into words. but trust me, it gets easier, and that voice gives you power. take it, itâ€™s yours.

text:
been meaning to tell you 5/12
-whatcha gonna do-
during the time i wrote this song, #metoo campaign was starting to get lot of attention. it's unbelievable how it came as such a surprise for so many, how lot of women get sexually harrassed and abused on a daily basis. 
powered by all the brave women around the world coming out with their stories, i decided to write a story of my own.
 first i wrote a song called "why you gotta be that way", where i tell the story in woman's perspective. 
in "whatcha gonna do", i try to get inside of the man's, the harraser's head. what is he thinking when he keeps on intruding someone's personal space? why he can't take no for an answer? what makes him act that way?
this was a very challenging song to write, and felt like a personal achievement once it was done. i hope these two songs will bring awereness and conversations. #beenmeaningtotellyou

washington (ap) â€” thousands of requests by men to bring in child and adolescent brides to live in the united states were approved over the past decade, according to government data obtained by the associated press. in one case, a 49-year-old man applied for admission for a 15-year-old girl.
the approvals are legal: the immigration and nationality act does not set minimum age requirements for the person making the request or for that personâ€™s spouse or fiancee. by contrast, to bring in a parent from overseas, a petitioner has to be at least 21 years old.
and in weighing petitions, u.s. citizenship and immigration services goes by whether the marriage is legal in the spouse or fianceeâ€™s home country and then whether the marriage would be legal in the state where the petitioner lives.
the data raises questions about whether the immigration system may be enabling forced marriage and about how u.s. laws may be compounding the problem despite efforts to limit child and forced marriage. marriage between adults and minors is not uncommon in the u.s., and most states allow children to marry with some restrictions.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:

washington (ap) â€” thousands of requests by men to bring in child and adolescent brides to live in the united states were approved over the past decade, according to government data obtained by the associated press. in one case, a 49-year-old man applied for admission for a 15-year-old girl.
the approvals are legal: the immigration and nationality act does not set minimum age requirements for the person making the request or for that personâ€™s spouse or fiancee. by contrast, to bring in a parent from overseas, a petitioner has to be at least 21 years old.
and in weighing petitions, u.s. citizenship and immigration services goes by whether the marriage is legal in the spouse or fianceeâ€™s home country and then whether the marriage would be legal in the state where the petitioner lives.
the data raises questions about whether the immigration system may be enabling forced marriage and about how u.s. laws may be compounding the problem despite efforts to limit child and forced marriage. marriage between adults and minors is not uncommon in the u.s., and most states allow children to marry with some restrictions.
